35
00:01:36,819 --> 00:01:40,060
So now let's take a look at some of the language on Language Takeaway.

36
00:01:42,259 --> 00:01:43,099
Language Takeaway.

37
00:01:44,299 --> 00:01:47,480
All right, in Language Takeaway, we've got a couple of words and phrases for you.

38
00:01:47,540 --> 00:01:50,719
The first one is I just got back.

39
00:01:50,939 --> 00:01:52,760
So to get back from somewhere, Marco.

40
00:01:53,180 --> 00:01:53,939
That's right, Jim.

41
00:01:53,939 --> 00:01:55,939
Jim just got back from Europe.

42
00:01:56,500 --> 00:02:04,060
And when you say I just got back is I recently or very recently returned from somewhere.

43
00:02:04,680 --> 00:02:04,939
That's right.

44
00:02:05,120 --> 00:02:07,920
To get back from somewhere means to return from that place.

45
00:02:08,379 --> 00:02:12,280
So in this dialogue, Jim just got back from Spain.

46
00:02:12,819 --> 00:02:14,580
Michelle just got back from lunch.

47
00:02:14,860 --> 00:02:16,759
This means to return from somewhere.

48
00:02:16,979 --> 00:02:17,240
That's right.

49
00:02:17,300 --> 00:02:22,259
So it can be a place, not only a country, but it can be, for example, the office.

50
00:02:22,259 --> 00:02:23,960
I just got back from work.

51
00:02:24,659 --> 00:02:27,120
Or I just got back from football practice.

52
00:02:27,319 --> 00:02:28,539
That's why I'm very sweaty.

53
00:02:29,020 --> 00:02:29,139
Right.

54
00:02:29,500 --> 00:02:34,620
So this obviously means that you are now not in the same place where you just got back from.

55
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:35,979
No, I'm from America.

56
00:02:36,319 --> 00:02:40,400
I went to Spain on vacation and I just got back from Spain.

57
00:02:40,500 --> 00:02:42,020
That means I'm in America again.

58
00:02:42,199 --> 00:02:43,000
Yeah, exactly.

59
00:02:43,080 --> 00:02:44,240
You're not still in Spain.

60
00:02:44,439 --> 00:02:44,580
No.

61
00:02:45,219 --> 00:02:47,879
All right, so that's for our first word.

62
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:48,879
Now let's go on.

63
00:02:48,879 --> 00:02:52,780
And Michelle said, oh, I'm so jealous of you.

64
00:02:53,039 --> 00:02:53,180
All right.

65
00:02:53,280 --> 00:02:55,960
Jealous is an adjective and a very, very common one.

66
00:02:55,960 --> 00:02:57,860
You can use it in many different circumstances.

67
00:02:58,039 --> 00:03:00,719
It means to want what someone else has.

68
00:03:00,879 --> 00:03:01,500
That's right.

69
00:03:01,560 --> 00:03:05,740
So in this case, Michelle is jealous that Jim went on vacation.

70
00:03:05,740 --> 00:03:07,879
So she wishes she could go on vacation.

71
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:08,580
That's right.

72
00:03:08,719 --> 00:03:09,900
I'm so jealous of you.

73
00:03:09,900 --> 00:03:16,400
Or if you see someone who has a new pair of shoes and you like the shoes because you don't have them, you can say, I'm so jealous.

74
00:03:16,400 --> 00:03:17,680
I love your shoes.

75
00:03:17,680 --> 00:03:18,300
That's right.

76
00:03:18,460 --> 00:03:20,360
So you say, I am jealous.

77
00:03:20,520 --> 00:03:24,800
Or if you are jealous of a person, you say, I am jealous of you.

78
00:03:25,340 --> 00:03:27,560
And so they were ending their conversation.

79
00:03:27,560 --> 00:03:28,680
And Jim said, you know what?

80
00:03:28,800 --> 00:03:31,699
It's been great to catch up with you.

81
00:03:32,159 --> 00:03:32,280
All right.

82
00:03:32,280 --> 00:03:34,639
This is a really important phrase to catch up.

83
00:03:35,020 --> 00:03:36,479
It means two different things.

84
00:03:36,479 --> 00:03:47,580
And we're going to talk about one meaning here today to catch up with someone like to talk to them about what they've been doing recently means to learn about their life because maybe you haven't talked in a long time.

85
00:03:48,080 --> 00:03:48,419
That's right.

86
00:03:48,699 --> 00:03:58,500
So maybe you haven't seen your friend in two years and you go out for dinner to catch up to talk about what has happened in your life recently.

87
00:03:58,919 --> 00:03:59,180
That's right.

88
00:03:59,259 --> 00:04:06,500
Or you can, if you see a friend on the street and you know that you haven't seen him or her in a long time, you can make a date to catch up.

89
00:04:06,759 --> 00:04:09,099
So Hey Marco, I haven't seen you in months.

90
00:04:09,379 --> 00:04:11,039
Let's catch up sometime soon.

91
00:04:11,240 --> 00:04:11,599
That's right.

92
00:04:11,599 --> 00:04:16,839
And that means to share information and to find out how you have been recently.

93
00:04:17,860 --> 00:04:18,120
All right.

94
00:04:18,259 --> 00:04:22,319
Now when he was getting out of the elevator, he said, this is my floor.

95
00:04:22,759 --> 00:04:24,899
Now we know floor, but my floor, what is it?

96
00:04:24,980 --> 00:04:25,339
My floor?

97
00:04:25,480 --> 00:04:25,980
Your floor?

98
00:04:26,120 --> 00:04:26,660
Whose floor?

99
00:04:27,160 --> 00:04:28,560
This doesn't make much sense, does it?

100
00:04:28,660 --> 00:04:34,939
Well, actually floor here means that this is the floor that I work on or the floor that I live on.

101
00:04:35,060 --> 00:04:36,839
It means the place I'm going to.

102
00:04:37,180 --> 00:04:37,240
Right.

103
00:04:37,339 --> 00:04:46,199
So we know floor, the ground beneath our feet in a building, but in this case we're talking about one of the levels of a building.

104
00:04:46,360 --> 00:04:47,699
So maybe the sixth floor.

105
00:04:48,079 --> 00:04:48,360
That's right.

106
00:04:48,540 --> 00:04:54,120
So if I'm in my apartment building in the elevator, I can say, Oh, stop the elevator.

107
00:04:54,160 --> 00:04:55,139
This is my floor.

108
00:04:55,139 --> 00:04:57,379
I want to get off the elevator.

109
00:04:57,660 --> 00:04:57,720
Right.

110
00:04:57,819 --> 00:04:59,199
This is where I live.

111
00:05:00,060 --> 00:05:00,439
All right.

112
00:05:00,439 --> 00:05:01,699
So a lot of great stuff there.

113
