140
00:06:01,439 --> 00:06:04,579
So now let's take a look at four key phrases on Fluency Builder.

141
00:06:06,339 --> 00:06:07,180
Fluency Builder.

142
00:06:08,740 --> 00:06:13,279
So there are some keys to these small talk conversations and they are definitely the phrases.

143
00:06:13,519 --> 00:06:16,399
The first one we have here is good to see you.

144
00:06:16,699 --> 00:06:18,879
So Jim says, hey, Michelle, good to see you.

145
00:06:19,199 --> 00:06:19,579
That's right.

146
00:06:19,699 --> 00:06:27,339
So we've chosen this phrase because it's very casual and very common to use as a polite way of saying, hey, how are you?

147
00:06:27,480 --> 00:06:28,160
Good to see you.

148
00:06:28,259 --> 00:06:32,420
I'm actually showing you that I'm happy that I am talking to you.

149
00:06:32,620 --> 00:06:34,860
So this is a very flexible phrase.

150
00:06:34,860 --> 00:06:37,980
You can say it at the beginning of a conversation when you just see someone.

151
00:06:38,120 --> 00:06:39,579
Hey, Marco, good to see you.

152
00:06:39,579 --> 00:06:42,740
Or at the end, you can say it was very good to see you.

153
00:06:42,879 --> 00:06:44,620
I hope to see you again soon.

154
00:06:45,060 --> 00:06:45,480
That's right.

155
00:06:45,519 --> 00:06:52,939
So maybe you can use it at the beginning if you just begin to talk to someone or if you're saying goodbye, you can say, well, you know what?

156
00:06:53,019 --> 00:06:55,980
I have to go now, but it's been good to see you.

157
00:06:56,319 --> 00:06:57,600
So very flexible phrase.

158
00:06:57,720 --> 00:06:58,339
That's right.

159
00:06:58,439 --> 00:06:58,759
That's right.

160
00:06:58,839 --> 00:07:03,939
Now, when Michelle thought that Jim was on vacation, Jim said, no, no, no.

161
00:07:03,939 --> 00:07:05,699
I wish I was.

162
00:07:06,360 --> 00:07:06,800
All right.

163
00:07:06,980 --> 00:07:07,600
I wish I was.

164
00:07:08,019 --> 00:07:09,879
I thought you were on vacation.

165
00:07:10,339 --> 00:07:13,540
So she thought that he was still on vacation in Spain.

166
00:07:13,759 --> 00:07:17,180
And he says, well, I'm not because, you know, here I am.

167
00:07:17,180 --> 00:07:18,680
But I wish I was.

168
00:07:18,860 --> 00:07:22,379
I wish I was in Spain right now because Spain is so nice.

169
00:07:22,740 --> 00:07:23,079
That's right.

170
00:07:23,139 --> 00:07:26,860
So it may seem a little bit strange, but it's actually completing the idea.

171
00:07:27,639 --> 00:07:31,959
So and basically we're using the verb to be because that's the question.

172
00:07:31,959 --> 00:07:34,060
Are you on vacation?

173
00:07:34,660 --> 00:07:37,459
No, I wish I was on vacation.

174
00:07:37,680 --> 00:07:39,639
So that means he's not, but he wants to be.

175
00:07:39,860 --> 00:07:40,459
That's right.

176
00:07:40,920 --> 00:07:46,459
OK, so now he actually had to get going and he used this exact phrase.

177
00:07:46,600 --> 00:07:48,819
He said, I must be going.

178
00:07:49,500 --> 00:07:50,399
I must be going.

179
00:07:50,560 --> 00:07:51,800
Now, remember this as a phrase.

180
00:07:51,860 --> 00:07:53,819
This is a good way to end a conversation.

181
00:07:54,180 --> 00:07:55,439
Maybe you have to go to work.

182
00:07:55,660 --> 00:07:57,420
Maybe you have your kids at home.

183
00:07:57,420 --> 00:07:58,899
You have to take them somewhere.

184
00:07:58,920 --> 00:08:00,540
So you say, I'm really sorry.

185
00:08:00,540 --> 00:08:03,500
I must be going, but let's see each other again soon.

186
00:08:03,819 --> 00:08:04,220
That's right.

187
00:08:04,360 --> 00:08:06,560
So you are politely ending the conversation.

188
00:08:06,819 --> 00:08:09,259
You are politely saying, I can't talk to you anymore.

189
00:08:09,740 --> 00:08:13,300
I must be going now, but it's been great to talk to you.

190
00:08:13,439 --> 00:08:13,620
That's right.

191
00:08:13,740 --> 00:08:14,240
Very polite.

192
00:08:14,399 --> 00:08:15,000
So remember this one.

193
00:08:15,100 --> 00:08:17,000
It's better than I'm going now.

194
00:08:17,379 --> 00:08:17,480
Right.

195
00:08:17,600 --> 00:08:18,120
We don't say that.

196
00:08:18,319 --> 00:08:18,339
Yeah.

197
00:08:18,339 --> 00:08:19,100
Or I have to go.

198
00:08:19,220 --> 00:08:22,540
Well, you can say I have to go, but it's nice saying, oh, you know what?

199
00:08:22,860 --> 00:08:25,199
I really like talking to you, but I must be going.

200
00:08:26,099 --> 00:08:29,560
And Jim also finished by saying, we'll speak again soon.

201
00:08:29,860 --> 00:08:31,579
And Michelle said, for sure.

202
00:08:32,039 --> 00:08:32,620
For sure.

203
00:08:32,840 --> 00:08:35,899
Now, Americans particularly love to say this phrase.

204
00:08:36,419 --> 00:08:40,059
For sure means yes, or I agree, or definitely.

205
00:08:40,620 --> 00:08:40,759
Right.

206
00:08:41,279 --> 00:08:42,820
You can use it as an interjection.

207
00:08:43,240 --> 00:08:47,220
So if I say, hey, Catherine, am I going to see you later on today?

208
00:08:47,440 --> 00:08:48,240
Yeah, for sure.

209
00:08:48,519 --> 00:08:48,960
For sure.

210
00:08:49,139 --> 00:08:49,500
There we go.

211
00:08:49,620 --> 00:08:53,399
So you're saying yes, absolutely, definitely, for sure.

